{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4b98c69e-91b0-41ad-9e55-4ca8fcc94cb4","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_014c2p2kXzkRQqvgPffX1gSt","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Running tests with crash dumps"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_014o88c1Xi9fdWwbGmfpZz6Q","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp/sv-de7775e875bb4c4d9e268ad70178b42f && dotnet test --blame-crash 2>&1","description":"Run dotnet test with blame-crash","initial_wait":60},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Run dotnet test with blame-crash"}],"interactionId":"1d7d4c66-90bd-408e-9f86-47ecaf4b0057","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to run tests with `dotnet test` and collect a crash dump if any test crashes the host. \n\nTo collect crash dumps when the test host crashes, I can use the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` environment variable (or `COMPlus_DbgEnableMiniDump` for older runtimes). For .NET, the relevant environment variables are:\n\n- `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` — enables crash dump collection\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4` — full dump (1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\n\n\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` — path/pattern for dump files\n\nActually, there's a simpler approach: `dotnet test` has a `--blame-crash` option that's specifically designed for this. It automatically collects a crash dump when the test host crashes, and I can optionally specify `--blame-crash-dump-type full` for full dumps or `--blame-crash-collect-always` to collect dumps even in non-crash scenarios.","outputTokens":505,"requestId":"7C10:203FDB:2887D9C:2CEAFC6:69F94964"},"id":"bb7c71f3-f40f-4e9f-a9b0-0d4321a2cee7","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:35:43.307Z","parentId":"6c68beed-3277-4940-8d0c-3d973d46a070"}
